The Familiarity of New Antisemitism
Why do so many Holocaust survivors sense emerging threats to Judaism before they become generally visible?
Because they know that the supposedly "harmless" hints can turn into accusations and eventually lead to discrimination that is then codified into law.
At that point, hysteria sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what is at stake.
Thus, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we too may survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential elections, it has been clear that we have every reason to listen.
But it is not only demagogues like Jean Marie Le Pen or other crude right-wing extremists in Europe who cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" often became opportunists of fascism or communism, without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we are dealing with people - with the "educated bourgeoisie" in connection with the mass media, politics, the government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often resembles that of the opportunists of these antidemocratic movements.
This is not the majority opinion in the Western world - not yet, fortunately - but it is the voices of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to the United Kingdom should be mentioned: Recently, during a dinner party in London, he referred to Israel as "this damned little country".
His vulgar expression is not particularly alarming.
What is rather alarming, however, are the reactions to it.
He was neither recalled by his government nor did the Blair government demand his recall. In public, the matter was dismissed as just another scandal.
The French press seriously portrayed the ambassador as a victim of British petty informers and not as a result of his own contemptible attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to the United Kingdom has many allies among Europe's elites.
Ambassador Bernard, however, did us a favor: Through him it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish resentments are.
As a columnist aptly put it: Israel has become a hate object whose very name one dares not to utter.
We, however, must not only dare to say it, we are even obligated to voice it.
Given the daily attacks against Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is a disgrace for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without worrying about their safety.
Anti-Semitic attacks are also reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, Holland and parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the denial of the Holocaust becoming commonplace. Nor may we remain silent about the comparisons that anti-Semites and anti-Zionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While in a Palestinian television broadcast Israeli soldiers are depicted as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we must "stand up to the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. They are almost hated everywhere."
During the television broadcast of a Friday prayer in Palestinian television, the preacher urged Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. No matter where you are, kill them and these Americans who are just like them."
What we should think about in connection with antisemitism is that it always begins with the Jews, but never ends with the Jews.
If Jewish hatred is not curbed, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore the task of Jews as well as non-Jews.
Currently, the points of attack in this fight are more blurred than ever before, because an amazing aspect of today's antisemitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of antisemitism always remains the same - namely to attack the Jews - it nevertheless changes its face, its strategy, its rationalizations and even its vocabulary.
Once, the Jewish religion was the target.
When this did not yield, the Jews were driven out or killed.
When in the 19th century the racial theory captivated people, Jews were attacked because of their belonging to a wicked race.
With the existence of the state of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is today disparaged as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with antisemitism.
Just like with other nations, it is perfectly legitimate to be critically opposed to certain political strategies and decisions of Israel.
Antizionism, however, is becoming increasingly similar to antisemitism.
Anti-Zionists sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I am only against the existence of Great Britain, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
You would not believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people, but hate their state.
And yet, there are people connected with Israel who claim to be exactly able to do that.
In various UN organizations, insults against Israel are on the agenda.
This demonization of the only democratic state in the Middle East is a core element of this new antisemitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of all that is good and the source of all that is evil," then within the UN the "teaching of contempt" circulates, as Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of the Canadian Parliament, expresses it.
This permanent portrayal of a nation as an enemy of humanity is in reality a campaign against the Jewish people.
Thus, the numerous anti-Jewish attacks in many countries are based on the demonization of Israel, which makes use of antisemitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this defamatory language in connection with the Middle East.
Compared to previous anti-Jewish outbreaks, today's antisemitism is less about attacking individual Jews, but rather an attack against the "collective Jew," that is, against the state of Israel.
Such attacks have, however, set off a chain reaction of attacks on individual Jews and Jewish institutions throughout Europe and Latin America.
Earlier, the most dangerous antisemites were those who wanted to make the world free of Jews.
The most dangerous antisemites today are those who want to make the world free of a Jewish state.
